WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.170
&gt;&gt; WITTENBERG: Hi, everybody. Thank you for
coming. My name is Evan Wittenberg. I work

00:00:04.170 --> 00:00:08.540
in the leadership development and people management
group as part of Google University. And we're

00:00:08.540 --> 00:00:14.179
very excited today to be introducing Tony
Schwartz as our next Leading@Google lecturer.

00:00:14.179 --> 00:00:18.630
Tony has an interesting history. Currently,
he's the founder, president, and CEO of a

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:22.020
company called the Energy Project which deals
all about with how to manage your energy,

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:26.090
not your time to be more effective and achieve
optimal performance in the workplace, at home,

00:00:26.090 --> 00:00:31.590
in life, et cetera. His background is really
interesting. He began his career as a journalist.

00:00:31.590 --> 00:00:35.510
He was a reporter for the New York Times,
associate editor at Newsweek, staff writer

00:00:35.510 --> 00:00:41.280
at New York and Esquire Magazines, and a columnist
for Fast Company. He also has a little dirty

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:44.989
secret from his past, co-authored the number
one, international bestseller "The Art of

00:00:44.989 --> 00:00:48.609
the Deal" with Donald Trump. So if you have
questions about his opinion of Trump, you

00:00:48.609 --> 00:00:52.040
can ask him later. And more importantly, wrote
a book call "What Really Matters: Searching

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:57.069
for Wisdom in America." What he's here to
talk to us today about is what I alluded to

00:00:57.069 --> 00:01:01.679
you before, how we can be more effective by
thinking about our energy throughout the day

00:01:01.679 --> 00:01:07.750
rather than our time. And he's actually piloted
his two-day version of the course here at

00:01:07.750 --> 00:01:11.210
Google that some people on the audience, raise
your hand if you've been through that course;

00:01:11.210 --> 00:01:14.580
a couple of people. So, you can look around
and ask them later if you want to know how

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:19.950
that was and we'll be announcing more about
that in the next few weeks. A couple of important

00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:23.420
things that Tony has asked, one thing that
you'll learn about in this book when you read

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:26.490
it, for those of you who got it, "The Power
of Full Engagement," is that the brain is

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:30.890
actually unable to multitask. So Tony has
asked to please close your laptops unless

00:01:30.890 --> 00:01:34.600
you're actually taking notes about this because
it's not possible to pay attention to both

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:38.590
even though we fool ourselves about that all
the time. There will be time at the end for

00:01:38.590 --> 00:01:42.381
questions and I would ask you to please come
up to this microphone at the end if you have

00:01:42.381 --> 00:01:46.530
questions about the talk. Hopefully, Tony
will keep you engaged so you won't be tempted

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:51.010
to go back to the Blackberrys and computers
throughout the talk. And I think without further

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:58.580
adieu, let me introduce Tony Schwartz. Welcome.
&gt;&gt; SCHWARTZ: Thank you. Thank you. Good morning.

00:01:58.580 --> 00:02:05.480
It's great to be here with a wonderful day.
This work comes out of a passion of mine that

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:09.729
began somewhere in my teens when other people
were doing things very different than I was

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:14.340
doing. I was trying to figure out what life
was all about and what made it possible, what

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:18.930
was it that made it possible, I guess, back
then to be a happier and more satisfied human

00:02:18.930 --> 00:02:24.620
being than I was growing up in a difficult
New York Jewish family. But over time that

00:02:24.620 --> 00:02:30.670
evolved into a passion around, what makes
it possible for a person to be all they're

00:02:30.670 --> 00:02:36.580
capable of being. What makes it possible for
a human being to build progressively over

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:43.090
their life a richer, deeper version of who
they are? And this work is about that. It's

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:50.230
nominally about helping organizations to be
more effective and more productive. It's nominally

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:55.640
about the difference about what it takes to
be a great leader. But I deeply believe that

00:02:55.640 --> 00:03:01.780
you can be a great human being and it may
or may not have any impact on--I'm sorry,

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:05.480
you could be--yes, you could be a great human
being and it may or may not have any impact

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:10.491
on whether you can be a great leader. But
you can't be a great leader if you're not

00:03:10.491 --> 00:03:17.820
a great human being. And so to me, the work
of leadership, the work of really being the

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:23.770
most effective you can possibly be begins
with the work of yourself. And so today, I'm

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:28.140
going to give you just a little taste of it.
You're going to see that it's oriented a little

00:03:28.140 --> 00:03:33.709
bit in the physical direction and that's largely
because everything begins with the body. I

00:03:33.709 --> 00:03:38.850
want to assure you that if you choose to,
if you're intrigued by this work that there's

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:46.069
a lot more to it and that we ultimately take
account of quite a wide variety of components

00:03:46.069 --> 00:03:51.980
that influenced your capacity to show up with
everything you've got in each part of your

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:58.870
life. So, what is it that starts us off? What
is it that makes it possible for me to get

00:03:58.870 --> 00:04:06.420
folks interested in bringing me into organizations?
And basically, it's this. It's that we have

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:13.960
developed a gap between demand and capacity.
So, here's the deal. In your lives, what happens

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:18.660
is when you're born, you obviously have very
low demand. You make a lot of demands but

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:24.600
you don't have a lot of demand. And your demand
progressively goes up over time. And in the

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:28.850
world we live in, it just keeps on going until
hopefully one day you drop off the face of

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:35.550
the cliff and your demands in the most graceful
way possible. But in the meantime, what's

00:04:35.550 --> 00:04:43.450
happening is that in the absence of a conscious
and intentional intervention on your part,

00:04:43.450 --> 00:04:50.250
the capacity you bring to the table is rising
no matter what you do. How many people here--well,

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:55.840
I don't want to ask that quite yet--the capacity
in your life is rising no matter what you

00:04:55.840 --> 00:05:00.650
do to your body, no matter what you do to
yourself. Your capacity just keeps on going

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:07.180
up, but it hits a peak at a certain point
in your life in the absence of intervention.

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:12.560
What age do you think that peak is?
&gt;&gt; MALE: Forty-five.

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:20.120
&gt;&gt; SCHWARTZ: Unfortunately, it is 30 not 45.
Now, in this group unlike most of the groups

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:24.650
I talked to, that's not yet such bad news
for you because you're not there yet. But

00:05:24.650 --> 00:05:30.770
guess what, even if you're not, I promise
you will be. And what happens then is that

00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:38.760
your capacity progressively diminishes over
time most especially, most especially at the

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:43.680
physical level. So for example, in the absence
of you're doing anything to keep this from

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:48.870
happening, from the age of 30 on, you will
lose one half pound of lean muscle mass every

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:55.169
year for the rest of your life. That's not
good news. And the reason it's not good news

00:05:55.169 --> 00:06:00.169
is that demand is not only--how many of you
would say that the demand in your life over

00:06:00.169 --> 00:06:07.860
the last two or three years is as high as
it's ever been in your life. Okay. And how

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:11.930
many of you expect given that you probably
pushed yourself pretty damn hard to get to

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:18.180
where you are today that over the next year
the demand in your life will finally begin

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:25.960
to diminish. So, in other words, your demand
is the highest it's been ever over the last

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:31.340
three years and you have every expectation
that it's going to continue to rise at a minimum

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:36.770
not to diminish. Let me ask you this question.
How many of you think that along with your

00:06:36.770 --> 00:06:44.130
demand your capacity will rise systematically
to keep pace with your demand over the next

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:51.060
period of time? Houston, we got a problem.
It's this problem, it's this gap, and that's

00:06:51.060 --> 00:07:00.460
the game we're in the business of trying to
address. So, the issue is that when it comes

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:07.650
to meeting demand, the number one resource
most of us use, naturally use, instinctively

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:13.320
use is our time. So, if you've got more demand,
you put in more hours. And I'm sure that many

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:19.350
of you are putting in a lot of hours. And
in fact, organizations, even progressive organizations

00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:23.669
like Google, even if it doesn't say it, even
if it has all sorts of wonderful things to

00:07:23.669 --> 00:07:30.400
give you an opportunity not to be working
does in fact value you to a considerable degree

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:36.979
based on the number of hours it's perceived
that you invest. Now, that's great for a certain

00:07:36.979 --> 00:07:43.740
period of time. But when you reach the limit
of the number of hours you have available

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:49.650
to invest, you've got a problem when it comes
to expanding your capacity, don't you. How

00:07:49.650 --> 00:07:54.210
many people here would like me to stop, spend
a few minutes giving you some advice on how

00:07:54.210 --> 00:08:00.400
to use your free hours? So, we're already.
That dance card is already full, isn't it?

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:07.069
That dance card is fall and the bottom line
is that time is finite. You've got 168 hours

00:08:07.069 --> 00:08:11.699
in the week. You're never going to have another
hour and you already don't have any free but

00:08:11.699 --> 00:08:16.440
I guess you're--but I know that your demand
is rising. So, that's not going to solve your

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:22.760
problem if we are going to make it possible
to meet the increasing demand in our lives,

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:26.860
to take account of the fact that we live in
a more complex world, what you're going to

00:08:26.860 --> 00:08:31.509
have to do is you're going to have to find
a way other than time to get more done. In

00:08:31.509 --> 00:08:36.080
other words, you're going to have to get more
than in less time. And the only way that we

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:41.530
have recognized that that really fundamentally
is possible is to go after a different resource

00:08:41.530 --> 00:08:47.600
and that resource is energy. And the reason
energy is a good resource to use is because

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:53.300
energy unlike time is inside you. Time is
outside you. It moves by you like a train

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:58.270
and once it's gone, it's gone forever. But
energy is inside you and it can be systematically

00:08:58.270 --> 00:09:06.360
expanded and it can be regularly renewed.
So energy is a fabulous resource to put it

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:11.420
in your disposal. But what is energy? What
is energy? Because it's easy to say energy;

00:09:11.420 --> 00:09:17.180
there's all kinds of energy and, you know,
it's easy to get real soft on the idea of

00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:23.110
energy. One of the reasons that organizations
use hours is they're very clear to calibrate,

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:27.120
minutes, hours, days, that's really easy to
calibrate. Energy is more ambiguous, more

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:33.350
subjective. So what is energy? Well, it turns
out, actually, energy has been defined. Energy

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:37.740
is the capacity to do work, that's what you
go in your physics courses, right? Energy

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:44.170
is the capacity to do work. So in other words,
in simple terms, if you have more energy,

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:49.990
you have more capacity, don't you? So in other
words, if I can help you to systematically

00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:54.930
build the reservoir of energy that you have
available, if I could put more fuel in your

00:09:54.930 --> 00:10:01.490
tank then presumably you'll have more capacity.
We tend to focus on skills and competencies,

00:10:01.490 --> 00:10:06.050
that's the life you've lived. You've all developed
an enormous number of skills, you've had all

00:10:06.050 --> 00:10:11.050
kinds of achievements around skills and you've
been measured by how many of those skills

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:15.320
you have. You've got into Google because you
have more than most people, way more than

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:23.100
most people. But here's the problem in a demand-laden
world with focusing simply on capacity. I'm

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:30.250
sorry, on competency. Capacity is underneath
competency. Capacity is what makes it possible

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:35.519
for you to bring your skill and talent to
life. You can't run on empty, although a lot

00:10:35.519 --> 00:10:40.390
of us try to do it. So if you are trying to
bring your skill and talent to life but you

00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:45.060
are, you didn't sleep a lot last night or
you don't eat the right foods, or you've got

00:10:45.060 --> 00:10:49.040
the wrong emotional state, or you weren't
good at focusing your attention, or your level

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:54.740
of commitment and passion isn't all that high,
these are all components of capacity, then

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:58.170
you're not going to be able to do it. And
we all know people, and we all know times

00:10:58.170 --> 00:11:03.160
in our lives when you--despite your enormous
skill and talent, haven't been able to deliver

00:11:03.160 --> 00:11:11.810
it, particularly under pressure. In a human
being, I'm sorry--in a car, you need one source

00:11:11.810 --> 00:11:17.339
of energy to get the thing to go, and mostly
it's been fuel. Now it's starting to change

00:11:17.339 --> 00:11:23.540
but it still going to primarily be one source
of energy. But a human being--a human being

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:30.839
requires a much more complex set of energies,
energy in the human system is multidimensional.

00:11:30.839 --> 00:11:37.260
We need four separate sources of energy in
order to be able to perform at our best, each

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:42.680
one of them is necessary, none of them is
sufficient by itself and they deeply influence

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:48.959
one another. So you can't get by--or I shouldn't
say get by, you can get by using only one

00:11:48.959 --> 00:11:53.390
or two of them to any great effect but you
can't operate at your best if you do that.

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:59.390
So what are these four sources of energy?
So I've already said that, so I don't need

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:06.110
to repeat it. The four--the four sources of
energy start with the physical, why? Because

00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:13.290
the physical is the base, it's the--it's the
foundation on which everything else rests.

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:18.860
If you don't have sufficient physical energy,
is it going to influence your focus of attention?

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:22.830
Is it going to influence your ability to manage
your emotion under pressure? Of course it

00:12:22.830 --> 00:12:29.610
is. So, we have tended to make this not performance
relevant or relevant to performance in the

00:12:29.610 --> 00:12:35.120
work place, we've discounted how important
physical energy is, and we haven't systematically

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:40.240
focused attention on it, and in fact increasingly
in schools for kids where we're starting to

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:44.970
do work we see that they basically dispense
with the physical dimension. They don't pay

00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:50.700
attention to it at all. You know, if you're
not on a varsity team in high school, then

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:56.990
you're not getting any attention to your physical
capacity. Physical capacity has four components.

00:12:56.990 --> 00:13:02.709
It's the simplest of all the capacities because
of that. Number one, nutrition; you're ability

00:13:02.709 --> 00:13:07.970
to move glucose and sustain glucose at a certain
level in your body, that's number one. Number

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:14.500
two, fitness; how well you transport oxygen
through your body. Number three is sleep;

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:19.490
how well do you sleep, do you sleep enough
hours, do you sleep deeply enough. And the

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:23.810
forth is, and this is the one that people
don't pay much attention to is recovery or

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:29.019
renewal; the day time equivalent of sleep
because the body is designed to sleep twice.

00:13:29.019 --> 00:13:32.700
The body is designed to sleep for a longer
period of time at night and it's designed

00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:38.790
to sleep for a short period of time in the
afternoon. And so it's also designed, unlike

00:13:38.790 --> 00:13:43.480
a machine, it's designed to move rhythmically
between the expenditure and the recovery of

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:49.730
energy. And so you need to, as you'll see
when I get a little further into this description,

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:55.270
you need to learn to value intermittent renewal
during the day in the same way that you currently,

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:58.079
I don't want to say in the same way that you
currently value sleep because a lot of you

00:13:58.079 --> 00:14:03.060
don't value sleep very much. But in the way
you should be valuing sleep. Okay. So that's

00:14:03.060 --> 00:14:07.870
physical energy. Then there is the quality
of your energy. The quality of your energy,

00:14:07.870 --> 00:14:15.510
that's how you feel because how you feel profoundly
influences how well you perform, how well

00:14:15.510 --> 00:14:22.639
you lead, how well you interact with others,
there is a very specific set of emotions that

00:14:22.639 --> 00:14:27.950
are associated with sustainable high performance,
and I'm going to get to those and talk about

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:32.350
those in just a moment. So we've got quantity
of energy, we've got quality of energy, and

00:14:32.350 --> 00:14:36.861
then we've got focus of energy. So that's
the mental dimension. Focus of energy is what

00:14:36.861 --> 00:14:41.960
the Evan was obliquely referring to when he
said that I didn't want you to be using your

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:45.889
computers and Blackberrys. The reason I actually
didn't want you to is because it makes me

00:14:45.889 --> 00:14:53.639
feel bad. It makes me feel like you don't
care, like you don't love me, and I have a

00:14:53.639 --> 00:15:01.589
high need. But the focus of your energy is,
the work we do around this dimension and the

00:15:01.589 --> 00:15:09.529
importance of it is that for thousands of
years it has been understood that we do our

00:15:09.529 --> 00:15:15.240
most effective work when we focus on one thing
at a time. That's were the meditative traditions

00:15:15.240 --> 00:15:22.670
came from. We have lost that. Google is responsible
for a lot of that because of the number of

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:27.649
opportunities it gives us to interrupt our
attention, but there are thousands of ways

00:15:27.649 --> 00:15:34.010
now that we get our attention interrupted
and it's at extraordinary cause to your productivity.

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:38.560
It's also at extraordinary cause to the depth
of work that you do. You know that if you

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:44.180
go out and try to take a run for example,
that the first two or three minutes or the

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:50.310
first five minutes, how do you feel? You don't
feel very good, you're not warmed up, you're

00:15:50.310 --> 00:15:54.570
not feeling like your muscles are warm, like
you're loose, like you're in your rhythm.

00:15:54.570 --> 00:16:01.480
Well the same thing is true mentally, if you
try to begin a hard task for the first three

00:16:01.480 --> 00:16:05.750
minutes, or five minutes, or eight minutes,
or whatever it is for you, you're going to

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:10.459
be half there and half not there. You are
slowly dropping down into a state of absorption.

00:16:10.459 --> 00:16:15.940
If you interrupt yourself frequently then
what you are doing is you're interfering with

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:22.949
that level of absorption, and on average,
the average person stays on task in an organization

00:16:22.949 --> 00:16:29.510
in an America today for eleven minutes. Eleven
minutes on a task before they go on to another

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:35.270
task, but during those eleven minutes, they
interrupt themselves with something, an average

00:16:35.270 --> 00:16:40.910
of every three minutes. So you can see that
we've got a big interference with our ability

00:16:40.910 --> 00:16:45.360
to bring absorbed attention to the table which
is part of the energy equation. And then finally,

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:50.380
there is the one that sounds as soft as in
fact probably the most important which is

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:58.380
what we call the energy of the human spirit.
The energy of the human spirit is the energy

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:06.339
derived from the sense, from the experience
of purpose and from an alignment between what

00:17:06.339 --> 00:17:13.209
you say is important in your life and how
you actually live; and the better that alignment,

00:17:13.209 --> 00:17:19.409
the more powerful the source of energy available
to you. In fact, this energy drives, this

00:17:19.409 --> 00:17:25.750
is the "Why," the others of the "Hows." This
"Why" energy drives your behavior at all the

00:17:25.750 --> 00:17:31.470
other level. So, it's an additional source
of energy, emotionally, mentally, and physically

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:35.539
when you've got it in place. So four sources
of energy, if you got all those four sources

00:17:35.539 --> 00:17:40.649
of energy happening for you, if you've got
that full reservoir of them, then you could

00:17:40.649 --> 00:17:47.729
fire on all cylinders. How many of you got
those nailed, those four? Let's find out.

00:17:47.729 --> 00:17:51.559
You got a pencil, or you got something that
you can write on? I'm going to take you through

00:17:51.559 --> 00:17:56.559
a little energy audit; that's what we call,
a little energy audit to give you a sense

00:17:56.559 --> 00:18:03.640
of how you're doing in terms of these four
dimensions of energy. How much energy do you

00:18:03.640 --> 00:18:09.409
have available to you in each of these four
dimensions? This little audit is designed

00:18:09.409 --> 00:18:15.529
around what we have determined, and it's very
strongly research-based. If you go on our

00:18:15.529 --> 00:18:21.360
website, the energyproject.com, you will see
a database for everything that I'm talking

00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:25.649
about. So I'm not talking about these things
because they occurred to me as good ideas.

00:18:25.649 --> 00:18:32.710
This is our gathering of the research. So,
